{
  "Entropy is a measure of:": "",
  "The temperature of a system": "",
  "The disorder or number of possible microstates of a system": "",
  "The pressure of a system": "",
  "The heat content of a system": "",
  "Entropy (S) is a thermodynamic quantity that measures the randomness or disorder in a system. More precisely, it measures the number of possible microstates (arrangements) available to the system. Higher entropy means more disorder and more possible microstates.": "",
  "According to the second law of thermodynamics, the total entropy of the universe:": "",
  "Remains constant": "",
  "Always increases for spontaneous processes": "",
  "Can either increase or decrease": "",
  "Always decreases": "",
  "The second law of thermodynamics states that for any spontaneous process, the total entropy of the universe (system + surroundings) increases. For reversible processes at equilibrium, the total entropy remains constant.": "",
  "Which process results in an increase in entropy?": "",
  "A gas condensing to a liquid": "",
  "Water freezing to ice": "",
  "Crystallization from a solution": "",
  "A solid dissolving in water": "",
  "When a solid dissolves in water, the highly ordered crystal lattice breaks apart and the ions or molecules become dispersed throughout the solution, significantly increasing the number of possible arrangements and thus entropy.": "",
  "The third law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of a perfect crystal at 0 K is:": "",
  "Undefined": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "Negative": "",
  "Infinite": "",
  "The third law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of a perfect crystal at absolute zero (0 K) is exactly zero. At this temperature, there is only one possible microstate (perfectly ordered arrangement), so S = k ln(1) = 0.": "",
  "For a phase change from liquid to gas at the boiling point, delta-S is:": "",
  "Positive but very small": "",
  "Positive and large": "",
  "Vaporization (liquid to gas) involves a large increase in entropy because gas molecules have much more freedom of motion and occupy a much larger volume than liquid molecules. The entropy change is typically large (e.g., about 88 J/(mol*K) for many liquids, known as Trouton's rule).": "",
  "Which has the highest molar entropy at 298 K?": "",
  "Methane (CH4, gas)": "",
  "Diamond (C, solid)": "",
  "Iron (Fe, solid)": "",
  "Water (H2O, liquid)": "",
  "Gases have much higher molar entropies than liquids, which in turn have higher entropies than solids. Among these options, methane gas has the highest entropy because gas molecules have translational, rotational, and vibrational freedom that solids and liquids lack.": "",
  "For the reaction 2H2(g) + O2(g) -> 2H2O(g), predict the sign of delta-S:": "",
  "Zero, because only gases are involved": "",
  "Positive, because gases are produced": "",
  "Cannot be determined without more data": "",
  "Negative, because the number of gas moles decreases from 3 to 2": "",
  "The reaction goes from 3 moles of gas (2H2 + 1O2) to 2 moles of gas (2H2O). A decrease in the total number of gas moles means fewer particles in the gas phase and decreased entropy, so delta-S is negative.": "",
  "The Boltzmann equation for entropy is S = k ln W. What does W represent?": "",
  "The work done by the system": "",
  "The wavelength of light emitted": "",
  "The weight of the system": "",
  "The number of microstates": "",
  "In Boltzmann's equation S = k ln W, W is the number of microstates (possible molecular arrangements) and k is Boltzmann's constant (1.38 x 10^-23 J/K). More microstates means higher entropy.": "",
  "Standard molar entropy values are always:": "",
  "Equal to delta-Hf / T": "",
  "Zero for elements": "",
  "Positive (greater than zero)": "",
  "Unlike standard enthalpies of formation, standard molar entropies are always positive for all substances at temperatures above 0 K. This is because any substance above absolute zero has some molecular motion and thus some disorder.": "",
  "Entropy increases when:": "",
  "Gases combine to form a solid": "",
  "A gas is compressed to a smaller volume": "",
  "A complex molecule breaks into simpler ones": "",
  "A solution crystallizes": "",
  "Entropy increases when a complex molecule breaks into simpler ones because this increases the total number of particles and the number of possible arrangements. More particles with more degrees of freedom means more microstates and higher entropy.": "",
  "What does the term 'entropy' mean?": "",
  "The heat transferred at constant pressure": "",
  "The speed at which a reaction occurs": "",
  "The total energy stored in a system": "",
  "A thermodynamic property that measures the degree of disorder or randomness in a system": "",
  "Entropy (S) is a thermodynamic state function that quantifies the degree of disorder or randomness in a system. At the molecular level, it reflects the number of ways energy can be distributed among the particles (microstates). Its units are J/(mol*K).": "",
  "What does 'spontaneous process' mean in thermodynamics?": "",
  "A process that occurs rapidly": "",
  "A process that releases heat": "",
  "A process that occurs on its own without continuous external intervention, once initiated": "",
  "A process that reaches equilibrium instantly": "",
  "A spontaneous process is one that has a natural tendency to occur without continuous external energy input. It does NOT necessarily mean the process is fast; diamond converting to graphite is spontaneous but takes geological time. Spontaneity is determined by delta-G, not rate.": "",
  "What does the term 'microstate' mean?": "",
  "A specific arrangement of particles and distribution of energy in a system": "",
  "The state of a system at absolute zero": "",
  "The smallest possible state of matter": "",
  "A state where all particles are at rest": "",
  "A microstate is one particular arrangement of all the particles in a system with a specific distribution of energy. A system with many possible microstates has high entropy because there are many ways the particles can be arranged while maintaining the same macroscopic properties.": "",
  "What does the 'second law of thermodynamics' mean?": "",
  "Heat always flows from cold to hot objects": "",
  "Energy cannot be created or destroyed": "",
  "Entropy is always zero at absolute zero": "",
  "The total entropy of the universe increases for any spontaneous process": "",
  "The second law states that the entropy of the universe (system + surroundings) always increases for spontaneous processes: delta-S(universe) = delta-S(system) + delta-S(surroundings) > 0. This law gives directionality to natural processes.": "",
  "What does 'Trouton's rule' mean?": "",
  "The entropy of vaporization for many liquids is approximately 88 J/(mol*K) at their normal boiling points": "",
  "The total entropy of a closed system never changes": "",
  "The entropy of fusion is always positive": "",
  "All gases have the same molar entropy at STP": "",
  "Trouton's rule states that for many non-hydrogen-bonded liquids, the standard entropy of vaporization at the normal boiling point is approximately 88 J/(mol*K). Liquids with strong intermolecular forces (like water) have higher values because more energy is needed to overcome those forces.": "",
  "What does 'positional entropy' mean?": "",
  "The entropy of a substance at a specific position in the periodic table": "",
  "The entropy associated with the number of positions or locations available to particles in a system": "",
  "The entropy change when a substance changes position from reactant to product": "",
  "The entropy of a GPS tracking system": "",
  "Positional entropy (also called configurational entropy) refers to the entropy associated with the spatial distribution of particles. A gas has higher positional entropy than a liquid because gas molecules can occupy a much larger volume, giving them more possible positions.": "",
  "What does the term 'reversible process' mean in thermodynamics?": "",
  "An idealized process where the system is always in equilibrium and can be reversed with an infinitesimal change, with no increase in total entropy": "",
  "A process that occurs in the reverse direction when considering all relevant process factors": "",
  "A process that happens twice due to the well-established relationship between process trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Any process that can be undone when the interaction between process and reversible factors is taken into full account": "",
  "A reversible process is an idealized process that proceeds through a series of equilibrium states and can be exactly reversed by an infinitesimal change in conditions. For reversible processes, delta-S(universe) = 0. Real processes are irreversible with delta-S(universe) > 0.": "",
  "What does 'delta-S-surroundings' mean?": "",
  "The entropy change of the system multiplied by -1": "",
  "The entropy change that equals zero for all processes": "",
  "The entropy change of the surroundings, calculated as -delta-H / T for a process at constant temperature and pressure": "",
  "The total entropy of everything outside the laboratory": "",
  "The entropy change of the surroundings is calculated as delta-S(surr) = -delta-H(sys) / T. An exothermic reaction (negative delta-H) increases the entropy of the surroundings (positive delta-S-surr), while an endothermic reaction decreases it.": "",
  "What does 'absolute entropy' mean?": "",
  "The entropy of a substance in absolute vacuum": "",
  "The entropy value determined relative to the reference point of zero entropy at 0 K for a perfect crystal": "",
  "The maximum possible entropy of any substance": "",
  "The entropy without any sign (positive or negative)": "",
  "Absolute entropy (also called third-law entropy) is the entropy of a substance measured from the reference point established by the third law of thermodynamics: S = 0 at 0 K for a perfect crystal. Unlike enthalpy, we can determine absolute values of entropy.": "",
  "What does the term 'residual entropy' mean?": "",
  "The small amount of entropy in a vacuum": "",
  "The difference between system and surroundings entropy": "",
  "The entropy left over after a reaction is complete": "",
  "Entropy that remains in a crystal at 0 K due to molecular disorder that persists even at absolute zero": "",
  "Residual entropy is the entropy that remains at absolute zero for substances that do not form a perfect crystal. For example, CO molecules can orient as CO or OC in the crystal, creating disorder even at 0 K. Ice also has residual entropy due to hydrogen bond arrangements.": "",
  "A chemist observes that the dissolution of ammonium nitrate in water is endothermic (delta-H = +25.7 kJ/mol) yet spontaneous at 25 degrees C. What must be true about delta-S for this process?": "",
  "Delta-S is irrelevant to spontaneity": "",
  "Delta-S must be negative": "",
  "Delta-S must be positive and large enough that T(delta-S) > delta-H": "",
  "Delta-S must be zero": "",
  "For a spontaneous endothermic process, delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) < 0. Since delta-H is positive, T(delta-S) must be greater than delta-H to make delta-G negative. This requires delta-S to be sufficiently large and positive: delta-S > 25,700/298 = 86.2 J/(mol*K).": "",
  "An environmental scientist compares CO2(g) (S = 213.7 J/(mol*K)) with CaCO3(s) (S = 92.9 J/(mol*K)). Why does the gas have much higher entropy?": "",
  "Because CO2 is lighter than CaCO3, as conventional Caco theory would suggest": "",
  "Because CO2 has more atoms per molecule, based on conventional assumptions about Caco": "",
  "Because gas molecules have much greater translational freedom and occupy more volume than molecules in a solid lattice": "",
  "Because solids always have zero entropy regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Gas-phase CO2 has much higher entropy than solid CaCO3 primarily because gas molecules have extensive translational freedom, moving randomly throughout their container. Solid CaCO3 has ions locked in a crystal lattice with limited motion. The phase of matter is the dominant factor in determining entropy.": "",
  "A student calculates delta-S for the reaction CaCO3(s) -> CaO(s) + CO2(g) using standard entropies: S(CaCO3) = 92.9, S(CaO) = 39.7, S(CO2) = 213.7 J/(mol*K). What is delta-S?": "",
  "-160.5 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "+81.0 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "+346.3 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "+160.5 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "delta-S = Sum S(products) - Sum S(reactants) = [39.7 + 213.7] - [92.9] = 253.4 - 92.9 = +160.5 J/(mol*K). The positive value makes sense because a gas is produced from a solid, greatly increasing the number of microstates.": "",
  "A physicist studying entropy considers what happens when a hot metal block at 500 K is placed in cold water at 300 K. The block transfers 1000 J of heat to the water. What is the entropy change of the universe?": "",
  "+1.33 J/K": "",
  "+5.33 J/K": "",
  "-1.33 J/K": "",
  "0 J/K": "",
  "delta-S(metal) = -1000/500 = -2.00 J/K. delta-S(water) = +1000/300 = +3.33 J/K. delta-S(universe) = -2.00 + 3.33 = +1.33 J/K. The positive total confirms this is a spontaneous process, as expected for heat flow from hot to cold.": "",
  "A biochemist studies the folding of a protein, which has delta-H = -40 kJ/mol and delta-S = -100 J/(mol*K). At what temperature does protein folding become nonspontaneous?": "",
  "It is always spontaneous": "",
  "200 K": "",
  "600 K": "",
  "400 K": "",
  "T = delta-H / delta-S = -40,000 / -100 = 400 K. Below 400 K, the exothermic enthalpy drives spontaneity (delta-G < 0). Above 400 K, the unfavorable entropy term dominates, making delta-G > 0. This explains why proteins denature (unfold) at high temperatures.": "",
  "A student is given four reactions and asked which has the most positive delta-S. Which reaction has the greatest entropy increase?": "",
  "2KClO3(s) -> 2KCl(s) + 3O2(g)": "",
  "N2(g) + 3H2(g) -> 2NH3(g)": "",
  "NaCl(s) -> Na+(aq) + Cl-(aq)": "",
  "H2O(l) -> H2O(s)": "",
  "2KClO3(s) -> 2KCl(s) + 3O2(g) has the greatest entropy increase because 3 moles of gas are produced from a solid. Gas formation is the strongest driver of entropy increase. Freezing water (negative delta-S) and ammonia synthesis (decrease in gas moles) have negative delta-S. Dissolving NaCl has positive delta-S but less than producing gas.": "",
  "A chemical engineer determines that an industrial reaction has delta-H = +50 kJ/mol and delta-S = -80 J/(mol*K). What can she conclude about the spontaneity of this reaction?": "",
  "Nonspontaneous at all temperatures": "",
  "Spontaneous only at low temperatures": "",
  "Spontaneous at all temperatures": "",
  "Spontaneous only at high temperatures": "",
  "When delta-H > 0 (endothermic) and delta-S < 0 (entropy decreases), delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) is always positive because both terms contribute positively to delta-G. The enthalpy term is positive and the -T(delta-S) term is also positive (since delta-S is negative). The reaction is nonspontaneous at all temperatures.": "",
  "An atmospheric scientist considers the entropy of the reaction: N2O4(g) -> 2NO2(g). Given S(N2O4) = 304.3 J/(mol*K) and S(NO2) = 240.1 J/(mol*K), calculate delta-S and explain the result.": "",
  "+64.2 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "-64.2 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "+175.9 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "-175.9 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "delta-S = 2(240.1) - 304.3 = 480.2 - 304.3 = +175.9 J/(mol*K). The positive value is expected because one molecule splits into two gas molecules, doubling the number of independent particles and greatly increasing the number of available microstates.": "",
  "A food scientist knows that liquid water freezes spontaneously below 0 degrees C despite having delta-S(system) < 0. How is this consistent with the second law of thermodynamics?": "",
  "The entropy of the system actually increases during freezing": "",
  "The exothermic nature of freezing increases the entropy of the surroundings enough to make delta-S(universe) > 0": "",
  "Freezing is not actually spontaneous below 0 degrees C": "",
  "The second law does not apply to phase changes": "",
  "Freezing is exothermic (delta-H < 0), so heat is released to the surroundings. This increases delta-S(surroundings) = -delta-H/T. Below 0 degrees C, the positive delta-S(surroundings) exceeds the negative delta-S(system), making delta-S(universe) > 0, satisfying the second law.": "",
  "A researcher studies the dissolution of NaCl in water. The process has delta-H = +3.9 kJ/mol. At 25 degrees C, the process is spontaneous. What minimum value must delta-S have?": "",
  "Greater than 13.1 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "It can be any negative value": "",
  "Greater than 130 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "Greater than 0 J/(mol*K)": "",
  "For spontaneity: delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) < 0. So T(delta-S) > delta-H: 298(delta-S) > 3900 J. delta-S > 3900/298 = 13.1 J/(mol*K). The actual delta-S for NaCl dissolution is about +43 J/(mol*K), well above this minimum, confirming spontaneity.": ""
}